Flight from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the opportunity to turn towards democracy, a market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke away from their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Until recently, the Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category.
Their economic and political failure was largely based on – actively supported by Russia – secessionist movements that sought to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping troops" in order to maintain control.
For a long time, people have feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn into hot ones.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions — because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve a breakthrough toward a market economy and democracy.
To this end, the European Union's "neighboring policy" has also contributed.
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Now dangerously close to becoming a failed state, Georgia has meanwhile turned towards the West.
The success of the various "color revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also triggered change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at drawing closer to the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova aimed at peacefully restoring the territorial integrity of these countries.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia regained its independence in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with severe economic problems, unsuitable for investments.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its main exports were metal scrap and wood, yet its economy grew.
In northeast Estonia, with its predominantly Russian-speaking population that had settled there during the Soviet era, Russia supported so-called "autonomy movement."
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
High taxes were imposed on the few Estonian products allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerve.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to realign its economy towards the West.
On the other hand, Western Europe did what it could to integrate the Baltic States—Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia—while at the same time striving to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and thus Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries, joining the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported in the same way by Western Europe.
Of course, Georgia appeared as a less attractive partner compared to the Baltic States; the 1990s were marked by coups, countercoups, and civil wars, during which two regions—Abkhazia and South Ossetia—essentially separated with the support of Russia.
The country has done its best to forget its dismal past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army has been strengthened, and the country's leadership is young, dynamic, and earnestly striving to move the country forward.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and by over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is striving to ease tensions surrounding Abkhazia and South Ossetia; Russia, however, accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
His main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to block reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also important.
Estonia has shown – at the time of its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument – that it is possible to resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must realize that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this can be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has a legitimate reason to hope that it will achieve real independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were?
The lack of reform successes is partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
The fact that the industrialized region of Transnistria—whose Russian- and Ukrainian-speaking population feared that the majority of Moldovans, of Romanian descent, planned closer ties with Romania—separated from Moldova dealt a serious blow to the country's independence right from the beginning.
A civil war followed, and in 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they still are today.
The independence of Transnistria has never been recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that lawlessness and corruption prevail there.
Moldova is highly indebted, unemployment is high, and its once prestigious wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Moldovan government representatives made four fruitless visits to Moscow in an attempt to convince President Vladimir Putin to seek a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin has asked the EU observer mission Eubam for help, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems the West lacks up-to-date knowledge about the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, both the EU and the USA learned about a proposed peace agreement only through a report that had leaked in Germany.
This, it seems, would favor Russia, as Moldova would recognize Transnistria as a legitimate unit within it.
If Russia has isolated the West in this manner, it would set a dangerous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
